krijk","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Markby, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1465–1528":"1465–1528","1467–Male":"1467–Deceased","1476–Female":"1476–Deceased","1493–1550":"1493–1550","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1430–Male":"1430–Deceased","1431–Female":"1431–Deceased","1500":"1500","1467":"1467","1465":"1465","1476":"1476","1497":"1497","1431":"1431","1430":"1430","<1493>":"1493","1550":"1550","1493":"1493","1528":"1528",",, England":"England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Markby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Markby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Randall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): common colloquial pronunciation of   Randolph  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Randell","meanings":["English: variant of   Randall  .","Americanized form of German   Randel  ."]},{"name":"Randon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel.","English: probably a variant of   Randall  , with assimilation of <i>n-l</i> to <i>n-n</i>.","French (northern): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Rando</i>, a short form of names based on the element <i>rand</i> ‘rim (of a shield), shield’."]},{"name":"Randol","meanings":["English: altered form of   Randall  ."]},{"name":"Randal","meanings":["English: variant of   Randall  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Randal in Gulen, a compound of Old Norse <i>runnr</i> ‘copse, thicket, grove’ + <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’."]},{"name":"Randles","meanings":["English and Irish (Louth): variant of   Randall  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Ireland this is sometimes a variant of   Reynolds  ."]},{"name":"Randle","meanings":["English: variant of   Randall  .","Americanized form of German   Randel   or of its Bavarian variant <b>Randl</b>."]},{"name":"Rendell","meanings":["English (Somerset, Devon, and Dorset): variant of   Randall  ."]},{"name":"Randel","meanings":["English: variant of   Randall  .","South German: variant of   Rand   3."]},{"name":"Randolph","meanings":["English and German: from <i>Randolf</i>, an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>rand</i> ‘rim (of a shield), shield’ + <i>wolf</i> ‘wolf’. This was introduced into England by the Normans in Old French forms of two different ancient Germanic personal names which became confused with each other: <i>Randulf</i> (from <i>rand</i> ‘(shield-)edge’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’) and <i>Rannulf</i> (from <i>hraf(a)n</i> ‘raven’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’).","History: An American family bearing this surname are descended from William Randolph (<i>c.</i> 1651–1711), a planter and merchant, a member of a family that originally came from Sussex, England. William Randolph emigrated from Warwickshire to VA <i>c.</i> 1673. He was a forebear of Thomas Jefferson and Robert E. Lee. Randolph had seven sons, each of whom inherited an estate, the name of which was sometimes added to their own, such as Sir John Randolph of Tazewell. His great-grandsons included Edmund Randolph (1753–1813), first attorney general of the US and one of the framers of the US Constitution, and the diplomat and statesman John Randolph of Roanoke (1773–1833), who served as US minister to Russia."]},{"name":"Rendall","meanings":["English: variant of   Randall  .","Scottish: habitational name from Rendall (Orkney), named with a stream-name of uncertain origin + Old Norse <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’.","In some cases possibly also an Americanized form of Swedish   Rendahl  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Henryson Randall was born in 1465, in Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jarl Henry Rognvaldson Randall, was 35 and his mother, Mrs Anne Randall, was 34. He married Magdalena T Kamp in 1497, in Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1528, in Sussex, England, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1465–1528":"1465–1528","1467–Male":"1467–Surnud","1476–Female":"1476–Surnud","1493–1550":"1493–1550","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1431–Female":"1431–Surnud","1500":"1500","1467":"1467","1465":"1465","1476":"1476","1497":"1497","1431":"1431","1430":"1430","<1493>":"1493","1550":"1550","1493":"1493","1528":"1528",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Little Missenden, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Markby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Markby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1465–1528":"1465–1528","1467–Male":"1467–Kuollut","1476–Female":"1476–Kuollut","1493–1550":"1493–1550","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1431–Female":"1431–Kuollut","1500":"1500","1467":"1467","1465":"1465","1476":"1476","1497":"1497","1431":"1431","1430":"1430","<1493>":"1493","1550":"1550","1493":"1493","1528":"1528",",, England":"Englant